<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Mines Minion Cultures<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12258'>James "Junkit!" Kearns</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=12258&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 22, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> This is an article I wrote a while back... Just posting it to get a post in and see what people may think.<br>
<br>
The most striking aspect of the Mines of Moria expansion would have to be the ability to effectively combine your shadow cultures. You have always been able to combine Free-People&#8217;s cultures in Fellowship, and Mines certainly adds to this, but Shadow has in the majority been a one-culture game. The most striking of these strategies involves direct damage and the manipulation of the One Ring. Both of which were evident, but inconsistent in Fellowship.<br>
<br>
Both strategies involve the Ringwraith culture in combination with either Isengard or Sauron. It is surprising to discover how well these cultures work with each other in the two combinations. As it stands now the strategies I am about to outline come complete with a Free-People&#8217;s counter-strategy, that is the risk you take. But remember the more unique you strategy is&#8230; The greater the problem is for your opponent.<br>
<br>
Let us consider an Isengard/Ringwraith combination, which in the majority focuses on the One Ring. The first obvious tool here is forcing the One Ring onto Frodo&#8217;s finger, which can be achieved with Saruman&#8217;s Reach. Most players will put on the One Ring instead of exerting two companions, and even then two exertions is a mighty good thing. Once the One Ring is on the finger play Too Much Attention, which is a response meaning cards like O Elbereth! Glithoniel! will not counter it. Now the Free-People&#8217;s player is forced to discard the top 5 cards of his or her draw deck. When you pull this off, you can rest assured that not only have you annoyed your opponent but they will probably take the two exertions instead next time, guaranteeing you more wounds even if you don&#8217;t have another Too Much Attention in your hand. Having said this you can play it anytime the ring is on, with or without Saruman&#8217;s Reach.<br>
<br>
The next logical part to this combination is the Burden/Wound capabilities of the Ringwraith culture, the most obvious being the Twilight Nazgul. If you have managed to get the One Ring on the finger with Saruman&#8217;s Reach, and happen to have a Twilight Nazgul out in play as well, then Wraith World would come in handy. Spotting the Twilight Nazgul and the One Ring on the finger you can add 3 burdens. Then lets say the Twilight Nazgul is Ulaire Neyla who only needs to spot 2 burdens or 2 wounds to become fierce and damage+1, you&#8217;ve just created a triple blow. The Twilight Witch King is also valuable, being able to add 2 wounds to the ringbearer allowing Neyla to once again grow in power. Then to add to this, you could of played It Wants to Be Found back in the Manoeuvre phase to add yet another burden. So with only one Isengard Minion, Ulaire Neyla and maybe even the Twilight Witch King you have managed to add 4 burdens and possibly two wounds without considering what happens in a Skirmish. This strategy too is not entirely confined to one Skirmish phase; you may be able to span it out across two sites as long as your deck is structured properly.<br>
<br>
There is another advantage to be exploited here using the Uruk Spy and the Twilight Ulaire Enquea. Uruk Spy comes in handy if the One Ring is in use, allowing the possibility of adding more and more burdens, Uruk Captain can be used to recover any Isengard Minions discarded by Uruk Spy. The same also goes for Enquea, who if successful in the skirmish can firstly add a wound or spot 5 burdens to add a second wound to the ringbearer. Spotting 5 burdens becomes easy in decks like this as the majority of decks do not have burden removing capabilities. Even if the burden removing Sam is a worry for you, you can always add Helpless to you deck to shut him down. Then Finally The Summit of Amon Hen at site 9 will allow you to draw a card for every burden, giving you a high chance of doubling the cards in your hand for the final battle, sound inviting? You should also throw in some Uruk Scouts to ensure that any Ranger cards are kept at bay, especially Versatility.<br>
<br>
The beauty of this strategy is it has probably not been taken into consideration in the construction of your opponent&#8217;s Free-Peoples section. It also relies on the use of the One Ring, but can still incur a hefty blow without it. The danger is once your opponent clues into the strategy, they can counter it if playing the right cards. The trick then is to have a contingency plan. With that in mind I would add Savagery and Veils Removed to make you Minions more potent in battle. Overall however you can effectively wipe out a ringbearer in two sites without any trouble whatsoever.<br>
<br>
The second combination I want to look at is the Ringwraith/Sauron combination, which once again uses burdens, with the added bonus of direct damage. The majority of Minions in this strategy would be Nazgul, and mainly Twilight Nazgul using some of the strategy from the previous combination. The important aspect to note here is you only need a few Orcs to make this work. I regularly use the Orc Ambusher and Orc Scout for its low shadow cost and a vitality of 2, however any low cost Orc with a vitality greater than 1 will do. You should remember that Orc Scout can also shut down any Ranger cards.<br>
<br>
You need to play Orc Bowmen so that it is possible to have one Orc out and still have 4 archery fire. You will also want to play Hate, which will allow you to dispatch any companion to the surprise of the opponent. If you manage to get a Tower Assassin out you can play two Hates which means most companions would be in lots of trouble, early on in the game as well. The point here however is to ensure you use the Hates wisely and not just at random.<br>
<br>
The Nazgul abilities and the Direct Damage of the Orcs will generally ensure you will find a few burdens on the ringbearer. With this in mind The Eye of Sauron will increase the rate in which you move through your deck, so if you find this strategy too slow in terms of card turnover there is a solution. Then if you manage to spot the One Ring on the ringbearer&#8217;s finger, which may only be more likely at the later sites, you can play Southern Spies, which will force the Free-People player to discard their whole hand.<br>
<br>
Obviously the major bane of any Sauron deck and this strategy is the dreaded Sleep Caradhras, which means you need to direct as much as you can to Gandalf to keep him in the shadow where he belongs. Having said this however, do not be afraid, you just need to consider this in your deck design. <br>
<br>
The final thought here is it is pose a question of a combination Isengard/Sauron/Nazgul deck that ultimately would be too large to play for real. Needless to say however the combinations would be mind-boggling. Happy hunting Shadow players, and remember that multiculturalism is the &#8220;in&#8221; thing these days. <br>
